me from Cahaignes in Eure, France, or Cahaynes in Calvados, France, both probably named with a Celtic element meaning ‘juniper bush’."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Nicholas Keynes was born in 1405, in Winkleigh, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Keynes, was 26 and his mother, Elizabeth Denebawdo, was 51. He had at least 1 son and 1 daughter with Maud Moleyns. He died in 1425, in Devon, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 20."},"et":{"1405–1425":"1405–1425","1395–1425":"1395–1425","1425–1460":"1425–1460","1425–Male":"1425–Surnud","1380–1420":"1380–1420","1354–1416":"1354–1416","1425":"1425","1354":"1354","1420":"1420","1395":"1395","1460":"1460","4 May 1420":"4. mai 1420","1380":"1380","Bef. Jul 1416":"enne juulit 1416","1405":"1405","1416":"1416","Devon, England, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglisma